<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41037e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41037e">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41037e"> 37(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> iure mariti</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The husband was also entitled during coverture to his wife&apos;s leasehold property and to the rents and profits arising from them, and he could dispose of them without the concurrence of his wife. If he survived his wife he took them absolutely <mark><i>jure mariti</i></mark>. If the wife survived him, however, he could not dispose of them by will, and unless he had disposed of them in his lifetime, they reverted to the wife. <small> Maud I. Crofts, <a name="MICW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MICW"><cite title="source">Women under English Law</cite></a>, 1st ed. (1925) 34</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
